										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>There are now several books about the 2007-8 financial crisis, the best of which, in my opinion, is Adam Tooze’s ‘Crashed’. But the one that everyone remembers is Michael Lewis’s ‘The Big Short’, later made into a movie starring Christian Bale, Ryan Gosling, Steve Carell and Brad Pitt. Its narrative of misfits spotting the mistake everyone else was making is pleasing and elegant, so it’s easy to see why it’s so popular.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Sadly, however, it’s completely wrong: bankers didn’t sell insanely risky financial instruments because they misunderstood them, but because the trade was profitable, and they didn’t care if they might blow up the world.&nbsp;</p>


